english:
  title: Inscription on the Northern Wall
  author: Kim Si-seup
  language: eng
  text: |-
    One ladle of water, one bowl of rice—
    yet never partake idly of another's toil.
    For each meal received, give a day's labor in return;
    understand that this is righteousness.

    Do not fret over troubles of a single dawn,
    yet worry for the sorrows of a lifetime.
    Though the body grows lean, not from illness,
    find joy in a constancy that will not change.

    Honor the virtue of integrity and shame among scholars;
    disdain the deceptions and deceits of common ways.
    Rejoice not when others praise you,
    do not rage when others revile you.
    Remain serene, obedient to the natural order;
    walk unhurried, and something will be gained.

    Be like a cloud rising from the mountain—
    mindless, casting its shadow without intention.
    Be like the moon suspended in empty space—
    perfect and complete, reflecting all equally.

    In movement and stillness, in speech and silence,
    forget the body's form and return to the purity
    of the age of the Celestial Emperor.
    In bearing and conduct, establish your principles;
    hold in mind the ideals and standards
    of the Three Dynasties of Yao and Shun.

    That you might observe and examine yourself,
    I have written this upon the northern wall.
  footnotes:
    - The 'age of the Celestial Emperor' refers to the legendary era of Fuxi (伏羲), symbolizing primordial simplicity and virtue.
    - The 'Three Dynasties' refers to the legendary reigns of Yao (堯) and Shun (舜), and the Xia Dynasty (夏), representing the ideal age of virtuous governance in Confucian tradition.
    - This work is a moral exhortation inscribed as a personal reminder, following the East Asian tradition of wall inscriptions for self-cultivation.
